    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2671243713" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2671243713" />
    <a title="Quo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7392004-quo"><img alt="Quo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1393910036p2/7392004.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2671243713?book_show_action=true">Jan 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Quo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Quo" href="/user/show/7392004-quo">Quo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781873982778" href="/book/show/49530.Manon_Lescaut">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7392004-quo?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2671243713" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6742233023600166837">Abbe&apos; Prevost was indeed an interesting character, the author of <i>Manon Lescaut</i> managed to live a life full of false starts &amp; contradictions, while authoring a series of novels of which <i>Mano Lescaut</i> is the best remembered. This is in great measure because the work inspired operatic renderings by both Massenet, <i>Manon</i> and by Puccini, the latter with the Manon&apos;s full name as its title. But what seems somewhat more unusual is that rather than the author translating his life into novel form, he wrote </span>
  <span id="freeText6742233023600166837" style="display:none">Abbe' Prevost was indeed an interesting character, the author of <i>Manon Lescaut</i> managed to live a life full of false starts &amp; contradictions, while authoring a series of novels of which <i>Mano Lescaut</i> is the best remembered. This is in great measure because the work inspired operatic renderings by both Massenet, <i>Manon</i> and by Puccini, the latter with the Manon's full name as its title. But what seems somewhat more unusual is that rather than the author translating his life into novel form, he wrote this book as a kind of prequel to his own life, later following some of the same paths as Des Grieux, the man who loved the fictional Manon. <i>Manon Lescaut</i> is a tale of obsession, detailing how a relatively young, well-educated fellow from a noble family falls prey to a woman who becomes the total focus of his life, one intoxicating glance from Manon &amp; Des Grieux is forever mesmerized. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1582840586i/29029097.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>How very romantic, one might say but Manon becomes the lad's downfall and Des Grieux quickly forfeits his pending education at a seminary, invites his father's wrath, betrays the trust &amp; love of Tiberge, his closest friend and eventually becomes a cardsharp in order to keep Manon in fashionably good trim--fine clothes, a carriage &amp; horses, outings to the opera--in Paris, even after she shows little ability to remain faithful to the man. It isn't so much that Manon, poor but hardly an underworld character, doesn't love Des Grieux but rather that the things money can buy, pleasure &amp; amusement seem far more important to Manon than conventional morality, at least as it was envisioned in mid-18th century France. <br><br>Thus, this story is very much a period piece &amp; probably reads somewhat differently in the original French. The characters at times seem as if they might have wandered out of a painting by Manet or Caillebotte or Bonnard, among others who captured Parisian life in their day.<br><br>Unlike Des Grieux, Manon, fleeing a life of poverty, hasn't ever experienced differing outlooks on life &amp; while seemingly shallow &amp; easily distracted by all that money can by, does not seem an innately bad person. When Des Grieux meets her, Manon is at a way-station, en route to a convent where one guesses that she will be protected from her worst tendencies even if never developing a true "vocation" to take final vows as a nun. Rather, it is more as if she is being sent to a half-way house for rehabilitation but 2 centuries ago convents were often used as a means of education &amp; to provide security for young women as well as places of prayer, chastity &amp; austerity. In any case, in a love-at-1st-sight moment, Des Grieux shepherds Manon away in a carriage &amp; with what little money he has, they set up life in Paris. <br><br>Des Grieux's full title just happens to be "Chevalier des Grieux", suggesting knighthood or the French Legion of Honor but all honor is cast aside in favor of Manon. At one point, Dex Grieux does cast aside hope for sustaining the relationship as well &amp; returns to the seminary, begging his father's forgiveness. However, in time Manon seeks him out &amp; once again, Des Grieux flees a stable, professional life in favor of further courtship &amp; passion with Manon, commenting<blockquote>For my part, I felt that I would have sacrificed every bishopric in Christendom for Manon. In my eyes, separation from her would be the worst of misfortunes. I was prepared to endure not just abject poverty but the cruelest death imaginable, sooner than adopt a remedy that involved losing Manon.</blockquote>Yes, this does sound extreme, someone completely blinded by love but in the end when both Des Grieux &amp; Manon are jailed and Manon, in part for having bilked a wealthy older man who had fallen for her, is put on a ship with other prisoners bound for the wilds of Louisiana, Des Grieux bribes the appropriate members of the crew and follows Manon to America, where presumably there will be a fresh start for both. What more could a man do to prove his love? However, I disdain to give away the conclusion after the couple's day of reckoning in the New World of French Louisiana.<br><br>Of course all of this is the stuff of opera, at least as it was configured by composers a century &amp; more ago. There are differences between the Massenet and the Puccini versions of the Manon story but they are not major. I was fortunate enough to have seen both Natalie Dessay and earlier Renata Scotto as Manon opposite Jonas Kaufmann &amp; earlier Alfredo Kraus at Des Grieux in performances of the Massenet version of the opera &amp; a cast I can't begin to recall in the Puccini translation of opera based on the book by Abbe' Prevost. <br><br>If nothing else, in reading <i>Manon Lescaut</i> it was interesting to gain some further background on the novel that influenced both operas. What interested me most however was the introduction by Steve Larkin, who also did the translation in my edition of the novel, providing insight into the life of the author, Abbe' Prevost, including his two stints in a Jesuit seminary, a life in England in tow with a mistress but eventually jailed for non-payment of debts, traveling at times in disguise within France, eventually abiding with the Benedictines in a 2nd novitiate before again bolting from the religious life. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1582840586i/29029098._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>In the end, Prevost passed the remainder of his rather impoverished life as a journalist &amp; the author of multiple books, <i>Manon Lescaut</i> among them. It was said that the author, much like the characters in his novels was "often economical with the truth, deliberately equivocal, long on feelings of high moral virtue but often capable of a very ambiguous lifestyle." At the very least, all of this gave Abbe' Prevost considerable insight into the characters he was able to bring to life in his novels.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6742233023600166837" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

